Sure! To write an if/then statement in C programming language, you can follow these steps:

1. Define the condition you want to check using the if statement. For example, if (age >= 18) {
2. Specify the action to take if the condition is true using the curly braces ({}). For example, if (age >= 18) {
3. Use the else statement to specify the action to take if the condition is false. For example, else {
4. End the if/then statement with a closing curly brace (}).

Here's an example of an if/then statement in C programming language:

if (age >= 18) {
    printf("You are eligible to vote.");
} else {
    printf("You are not eligible to vote.");
}

In this example, the if/then statement checks if the age variable is greater than or equal to 18. If the condition is true, the statement prints "You are eligible to vote." If the condition is false, the statement prints "You are not eligible to vote."

Remember to always use proper indentation and spacing when writing C code to make it easier to read and understand.
